Jan Piotrowski Homework 4¶

From the first assignment, I obtained the SpeedDating imbalanced dataset with the following features:

  • pref_o_attractive: How important does the partner rate attractiveness
  • pref_o_sincere: How important does the partner rate sincerity
  • pref_o_intelligence: How important does the partner rate intelligence
  • pref_o_funny: How important does the partner rate being funny
  • pref_o_ambitious: How important does the partner rate ambition
  • pref_o_shared_interests: How important does the partner rate having shared interests
  • attractive_o: Rating by the partner (about me) at the night of the event on attractiveness
  • intelligence_o: Rating by the partner (about me) at the night of the event on intelligence
  • funny_o: Rating by the partner (about me) at the night of the event on being funny
  • shared_interests_o: Rating by the partner (about me) at the night of the event on shared interest
  • attractive_important: What do you look for in a partner - attractiveness
  • sincere_important: What do you look for in a partner - sincerity
  • intellicence_important: What do you look for in a partner - intelligence
  • funny_important: What do you look for in a partner - being funny
  • ambtition_important: What do you look for in a partner - ambition
  • shared_interests_important: What do you look for in a partner - shared interests
  • interests_correlate: Correlation between participants and partners ratings of interests.
  • like: Did you like your partner?
  • TARGET: Match or not.

This is interesting because the most important feature should be like, but the model can provide other insights.

I retrieved models from the first Homework: Logistic Regression and XGBoost.

Empirical distribiution¶

Based on Piotr Golach HW3 I checked empirical distribuion for the dataset.

In [46]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(9, 2, figsize=(12, 22))

axes = axes.ravel()

for i, col in enumerate(df.columns):
    if col != "TARGET":
        sns.histplot(df[df['TARGET'] == 0][col], bins=30, label='TARGET=0', stat='density', kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        sns.histplot(df[df['TARGET'] == 1][col], bins=30, label='TARGET=1', stat='density', kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f'Histogram for {col} by TARGET')
        axes[i].legend()

for j in range(i+1, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[j])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We can see that distribiuton of features isn't very skewed for 'importance' features, but it's differ for features with opinion (attractive, like, intelligence). This is quite intuitive - people rate importance independent of other person, and rate their opinion about second person based on Target - if they would date again this person.

SHAP comparision of two observations¶

I've chosen two observations. The first observation has main features: shared interests opinion and like. In other hand second observations' most influenced variables are attractive importance and interests correlation.

In [50]:
bd_obs_1.plot(bd_interactions_obs_1)
In [52]:
bd_obs_3.plot(bd_interactions_obs_3)

The insights are more clear for me than for LIME. For example from 'attractive importance = 10 decreases average response by 0.081, we can conclude that people who rate importance of attractivens very low are more likely to reject candidates.

Differences between packages¶

In [53]:
bd_obs_1.plot(bd_interactions_obs_1)
In [57]:
shap.plots.waterfall(explainer_shap(X_train.iloc[:1])[0])

For observation 1 the results from dalex and shap differ in attractive importance. The reason is that the order matter and different libraries in different ways estimate SHAP values.

Logistic regression¶

On the image below we can see logistic regression for observation 11, where oref_o_sincere is very important for Logistic regression (-0.141), but for XGBoost it is in interval and in general it is less important (-0.004).

bd_obsn.plot(bd_interactions_obs_n)
In [70]:
bd_obsn_lr.plot(bd_interactions_obs_n_lr)

        sns.histplot(df[df['TARGET'] == 1][col], bins=30, label='TARGET=1', stat='density', kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f'Histogram for {col} by TARGET')

In [21]:
# Next, for the same observations, calculate the decomposition of predictions, so-called variable attributions, using SHAP from two packages: dalex and shap
explainer_dalex = dalex.Explainer(clf_xgboost, X_train, y_train, label="XGBoost")

bd_obs_1 = explainer_dalex.predict_parts(obs1_x, type='break_down', label="obs1")
bd_interactions_obs_1 = explainer_dalex.predict_parts(obs1_x, type='break_down_interactions', label="Obs1+")

explainer_dalex_lr = dalex.Explainer(clf_logistic_regression, X_train, y_train, label="LR")

bd_obsn = explainer_dalex.predict_parts(obsn_x, type='break_down', label="obsn XGBoost")
bd_interactions_obs_n = explainer_dalex.predict_parts(obsn_x, type='break_down_interactions', label="Obsn XGBoost")
bd_obsn.plot(bd_interactions_obs_n)
